          "title": "The feast as political theater — power on display",
          "body": "Esther 1 opens with a narrator who understands imperial propaganda. Ahasuerus does not simply hold a feast; he displays — the verb is specific — \"the riches of his royal glory and the splendor of his great majesty for many days, 180 days\" (1:4). Six months. Every element of the feast is designed to communicate the same message: this king is incomparably great, and his greatness is real, material, and inexhaustible. Gold and silver couches. Mosaic floors of porphyry and mother-of-pearl. Wine served in golden vessels of various kinds (1:6-7). The historian Herodotus, writing of the same period, confirms the opulence of Xerxes' court. This is not a narrative invention — it is a portrait of a real empire at the height of its self-confidence.\n\nThe pastoral point is embedded in the display itself. Power that must be performed for 180 days to a captive audience of its own officials is power that feels the need to prove itself. Real security does not require a six-month announcement. The contrast the narrator is setting up — between the king who fills 180 days with display and the God who needs no audience — will be played out across ten chapters."
